<figure typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:U.S._Vote_for_President_as_Population_Share.png" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a7/U.S._Vote_for_President_as_Population_Share.png/300px-U.S._Vote_for_President_as_Population_Share.png" decoding="async" width="300" height="198" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a7/U.S._Vote_for_President_as_Population_Share.png/450px-U.S._Vote_for_President_as_Population_Share.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a7/U.S._Vote_for_President_as_Population_Share.png/600px-U.S._Vote_for_President_as_Population_Share.png 2x" data-file-width="699" data-file-height="462" /></a><figcaption>U.S. presidential election popular vote totals as a percentage of the total U.S. population. Note the surge in 1828 (<a href="/wiki/Jacksonian_democracy" title="Jacksonian democracy">extension of suffrage to non-property-owning white men</a>), the drop from 1890 to 1910 (when Southern states <a href="/wiki/Disenfranchisement_after_the_Reconstruction_Era" class="mw-redirect" title="Disenfranchisement after the Reconstruction Era">disenfranchised most African Americans and many poor whites</a>), and another surge in 1920 (<a href="/wiki/Women%27s_suffrage_in_the_United_States" title="Women&#39;s suffrage in the United States">extension of suffrage to women</a>).</figcaption></figure>
