<li id="cite_note-NBER2005-18"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-NBER2005_18-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-NBER2005_18-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFStanley_L._Engerman,_University_of_Rochester_and_NBERKenneth_L._Sokoloff,_University_of_California,_Los_Angeles_and_NBER2005" class="citation journal cs1">Stanley L. Engerman, University of Rochester and NBER; Kenneth L. Sokoloff, University of California, Los Angeles and NBER (February 2005). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20201111211244/http://economics.yale.edu/sites/default/files/files/Workshops-Seminars/Economic-History/sokoloff-050406.pdf">"The Evolution of Suffrage Institutions in the New World"</a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF)</span>: 16, 35. Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://economics.yale.edu/sites/default/files/files/Workshops-Seminars/Economic-History/sokoloff-050406.pdf">the original</a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF)</span> on November 11, 2020<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">March 10,</span> 2016</span>. <q>By 1840, only three states retained a property qualification, North Carolina (for some state-wide offices only), Rhode Island, and Virginia. In 1856 North Carolina was the last state to end the practice. Tax-paying qualifications were also gone in all but a few states by the Civil War, but they survived into the 20th century in Pennsylvania and Rhode Island.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=The+Evolution+of+Suffrage+Institutions+in+the+New+World&amp;rft.pages=16%2C+35&amp;rft.date=2005-02&amp;rft.au=Stanley+L.+Engerman%2C+University+of+Rochester+and+NBER&amp;rft.au=Kenneth+L.+Sokoloff%2C+University+of+California%2C+Los+Angeles+and+NBER&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Feconomics.yale.edu%2Fsites%2Fdefault